title: Fix segment fault for custom function
body:
**Description**: Fix segment fault for custom function.

In recent master, when onnxruntime_ENABLE_TRAINING_TORCH_INTEROP=ON, once the onnxruntime_training package is built and installed. If we run programs containing  'import onnxruntime', we will see a 'segment fault' errors printed in stdout. This bug seems to be there for a while, not sure why we did not see it earlier. 

The call stack looks like this:

```
>>>ninja --version
1.10.0.git.kitware.jobserver-1

Thread 1 "python" received signal SIGSEGV, Segmentation fault.
0x00005555556e26ff in tupledealloc (op=0x7ffd5a4113f0) at /tmp/build/80754af9/python_1553721932202/work/Objects/tupleobject.c:242
242     in /tmp/build/80754af9/python_1553721932202/work/Objects/tupleobject.c
(gdb) bt
#0  0x00005555556e26ff in tupledealloc (op=0x7ffd5a4113f0) at /tmp/build/80754af9/python_1553721932202/work/Objects/tupleobject.c:242

#4  std::unique_ptr<_object, std::function<void (_object*)> >::~unique_ptr() (this=0x7ffd5d029188 <onnxruntime::language_interop_ops::torch::OrtTorchFunctionPool::GetInstance()::instance_+40>,
    __in_chrg=<optimized out>) at /usr/include/c++/7/bits/unique_ptr.h:263
#5  onnxruntime::language_interop_ops::torch::OrtTorchFunctionPool::~OrtTorchFunctionPool (this=0x7ffd5d029160 <onnxruntime::language_interop_ops::torch::OrtTorchFunctionPool::GetInstance()::instance_>,
    __in_chrg=<optimized out>) at /home/pengwa/dev/onnxruntime/onnxruntime/core/language_interop_ops/torch/custom_function_register.h:16
#6  0x00007ffff7706161 in __run_exit_handlers (status=0, listp=0x7ffff7aae718 <__exit_funcs>, run_list_atexit=run_list_atexit@entry=true, run_dtors=run_dtors@entry=true) at exit.c:108

#10 0x0000555555776b62 in PyErr_PrintEx () at /tmp/build/80754af9/python_1553721932202/work/Python/pythonrun.c:646
#11 0x0000555555649869 in PyRun_SimpleFileExFlags (fp=<optimized out>, filename=<optimized out>, closeit=<optimized out>, flags=0x7fffffff4ce0)
    at /tmp/build/80754af9/python_1553721932202/work/Python/pythonrun.c:435
#12 0x000055555578ee5f in pymain_run_file (p_cf=0x7fffffff4ce0, filename=0x5555558c5920 L"/opt/conda/bin/ninja", fp=0x55555da35300) at /tmp/build/80754af9/python_1553721932202/work/Modules/main.c:427
#13 pymain_run_filename (cf=0x7fffffff4ce0, pymain=0x7fffffff4df0) at /tmp/build/80754af9/python_1553721932202/work/Modules/main.c:1627
#14 pymain_run_python (pymain=0x7fffffff4df0) at /tmp/build/80754af9/python_1553721932202/work/Modules/main.c:2877
#15 pymain_main () at /tmp/build/80754af9/python_1553721932202/work/Modules/main.c:3038
#16 0x000055555578ef7c in _Py_UnixMain () at /tmp/build/80754af9/python_1553721932202/work/Modules/main.c:3073
#17 0x00007ffff76e4bf7 in __libc_start_main (main=0x55555564aed0 <main>, argc=3, argv=0x7fffffff4f48, init=<optimized out>, fini=<optimized out>, rtld_fini=<optimized out>, stack_end=0x7fffffff4f38)

```

The reason is, singleton static instance of OrtTorchFunctionPool is destroyed after Python modules/functions are released.

There are two ways to fix it. 
1. UnRegister the python functions explicitly in some C++ class destructor for example ~TrainingAgent/~InferenceSessions or python module cleanup functions (https://docs.python.org/3/library/atexit.html). This will make sure all registered functions are still valid when we de-reference them.
2. Let OrtTorchFunctionPool don't own references on python functions, used borrowed ones only, so it does not need de-reference them during destructor. But there is a problem handling the forward(.apply) and backward(.backward) functions. When we register them, we only have a autograd Function's pointer, we need get the pointers of .apply and .backward and increase ref cnt for them, otherwise, the ref count is 0. So we still have to de-reference them in  ~OrtTorchFunctionPool, then we still have the segment fault prblem.

This PR is the a fix following the 1st approach. Please ignore the first and second commits (approach 2 and revert changes).

title: Implement Concat with Strided copy
body:
**Description**: 
Adds a `StridedCopy` function that implements a copy from strided tensor to another.

**Motivation and Context**
- This parallelizes the Concat operator, and can also be used in future to parallelize many other data movement operators (e.g. Transpose, Split, etc.).
- This operation is also required for the proposed data layout extensions to ORT. 

**Performance Characteristics**
All benchmarks measure the concatenation of two tensors with feature size 64 and variable batch size.

The PR introduces some overhead at smaller batch sizes: for axis 0, the new PR is at ~most half as slow as the current master with batch sizes less than 2048~ (not anymore, see below). For batch sizes above that, the performance is roughly similar (0.9x-1.05x). 

For multithreaded concatenations, speedup vs master scales slightly less than linearly with the number of cores, as would be expected. Of the (small) tested grid of parameters, the highest measured speedup is ~8x with 12 threads. 
At higher thread counts and high batch sizes, we also measure noticeable (1.5x-6x) speedups vs the parallelized PyTorch implementation.

(Please ping me for the detailed numbers)

title: Support optional type in ORT
body:
**Description**: 

Provide a data type implementation for the "Optional" type introduced in ONNX. 

Usage:

The usage from an end user-perspective should be fairly simplistic. If the model takes in an input that is of type `Optional(x)`, the user can just send in an `OrtValue` of type `x` and if they wanted to send in a `None`, they need not send any input at all. ORT internally handles such implicit `None`s.
* It is legal to skip sending in input(s) iff the model input(s) are marked `optional(x)`. The operators consuming such inputs have logic to handle such an occurrence.

Similarly, if the user receives an `OrtValue` corresponding to an output that is of type `Optional(x)`, then they simply need to run it through the API `HasValue()`. If that returns true, they are free to use the OrtValue with any API that supports handling type `x`. If the API returns false, they are in possession of a `None`. In Python, they will receive an explicit `None` as we tend to return Python objects as the output of Run().

Limitations:

1) `Optional(sequence(tensors))` has the same limitations as `sequence(tensors)` -users can't provide externally allocated outputs and can't using IOBinding.

2) `Optional(tensors)` have the same limitation for now - they can't be backed by externally allocated outputs nor can they be bound because in theory these optional types are still "non-tensors" . It may be possible supporting externally allocated memory and binding for optional types that are tensors with some amount of work, but the preference is to solve that problem when there is a concrete need.

**Motivation and Context**
ONNX compliance

title: Add PyTorch fallback for ORTModule forward exceptions
body:
This PR introduces the ability to fallback model execution from ORT backend to PyTorch backend

The fallback mechanism will be implemented at the ORTModule Frontend level only (using Python language) by catching/handling exceptions during diverse stages of execution (initialization and forward step initially). 

A family of Exceptions (`class FallbackException(Exception)`) will be defined and used to raise exceptions for code blocks that are subject to fallback to PyTorch engine. Only exceptions derived from `FallbackException` (as opposed to Python native `Exception`) are subject to specific fallback. This design prevents accidental fallback happening from unexpected bugs. There is an exception to this rule, in which a catch-all setting (or policy, as it will be defined below) can capture any exception (including native Exception) and trigger a fallback. 

The proposed fallback exceptions are: 

ORTModuleFallbackException(Exception): Base exception class for fallback
ORTModuleInitException(ORTModuleFallbackException): Trigger fallback for ORTModule initialization related exceptions
ORTModuleDeviceException(ORTModuleFallbackException): Trigger fallback for device related exceptions
ORTModuleIOError(ORTModuleFallbackException): Trigger fallback for I/O related exceptions
ORTModuleTorchModelException(ORTModuleFallbackException): Trigger fallback for PyTorch modules related exceptions
ORTModuleONNXModelException(ORTModuleFallbackException): Trigger fallback for ONNX model related exceptions. In this initial design, there is no granularity in the model export procedure, meaning that either the entire model succeeds to be exported or an exception is raised otherwise. It is not supported a scenario where part of the model is successfully exported and part of it is not (and an exception would be raised for the partial export) 

The fallback mechanism should be granular (through enumerations) and combinable, allowing the frontend to determine which failure(s) should be raised to the user and which ones should trigger the fallback mechanism.

Fallbacks for both evaluation and training mode are individually configured through different `GraphExecutionManager` instances.

In order to implement such granularity, policies (`class FallbackPolicy(IntFlag)`) were introduced and are defined as follows: 

* `FALLBACK_DISABLE`: Disable fallback entirely, useful for ORT engineers as it allows to catch issues early in the development process 
* `FALLBACK_FORCE_TORCH_FORWARD`: Force PyTorch engine during forward call, which is essentially a catch-all fallback. 
* `FALLBACK_FORCE_TORCH_BACKWARD`: Just a placeholder, no implementation is planned for now
* `FALLBACK_UNSUPPORTED_DEVICE`: Unsupported device configuration (e.g., more than one device per model, unsupported execution provider, etc.) 
* `FALLBACK_ UNSUPPORTED_DATA`: Unsupported input provided by the user or output returned by the model
* `FALLBACK_UNSUPPORTED_TORCH_MODEL`: Unsupported PyTorch model is specified. Initially a list of known models can be hard coded
* `FALLBACK_UNSUPPORTED_ONNX_MODEL`: A generic failure on model conversion to ONNX occurred 
* `FALLBACK_BAD_INITIALIZATION`: Unsupported PyTorch versions, missing PyTorch C++ extensions or any other initialization issue

A `FallbackManager` will map *exceptions* to *policies* in a way that when a fallback exception is raised by any component (e.g. Pytorch exporter, ORTModule frontend I/O validation, ONNX Runtime graph execution [1], etc.), such exception will be detected and based on the configured policy, ORTModule will either 1) yield the execution to Pytorch or 2) terminate the execution. Only exceptions that matches the specified policies result in fallback.

Below is a preliminary mapping between the policies and exceptions: 

* `FALLBACK_FORCE_TORCH_FORWARD`: `{ORTModuleFallbackException, ORTModuleDeviceException, ORTModuleIOError, ORTModuleTorchModelException, ORTModuleONNXModelException}`
* `FALLBACK_FORCE_TORCH_BACKWARD`: `{ORTModuleFallbackException, ORTModuleDeviceException, ORTModuleIOError, ORTModuleTorchModelException, ORTModuleONNXModelException}`
* `FALLBACK_UNSUPPORTED_DEVICE`: `{ORTModuleDeviceException}`
* `FALLBACK_UNSUPPORTED_DATA`: `{ORTModuleIOError}`
* `FALLBACK_UNSUPPORTED_TORCH_MODEL`: `{ORTModuleTorchModelException}`
* `FALLBACK_UNSUPPORTED_ONNX_MODEL`: `{ORTModuleONNXModelException}`
* `FALLBACK_BAD_INITIALIZATION`: `{ORTModuleInitException}`
 
The **ORTModule public API does not need changes**, therefore, there is no impact on the end user. Policies and any other setting can be internally updated (during ORTModule initialization) in an automatic (analysis of the user model during initialization) or manual fashion (during new releases/patches) 

When fallback is triggered, users can be notified through warning messages, which are already handled by an internal existing logger setting.

title: Improve performance of Pad CUDA kernel
body:
**Description**: 

Most image models use the `Pad` operation to pad only along the `height` and `width` dimensions (i.e.) they convert tensors of shape [N, C, H, W] to [N, C, H + pad_h, W +pad_w]. Our current implementation for Pad in CUDA is too "generic" (processes N-D tensors accounting for possible padding in all dims) to optimally process this often-occurring use-case. This change adds logic to recognize this special case and adds a specialized implementation (Torch-inspired) for the same.

This change closes the gap with Torch for model in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/8166. These gains should be applicable to all image models using such padding patterns.

The existing unit tests for Pad are very exhaustive and there are a good number of tests using the new specialized code path. No new unit tests required for this change. 

**Motivation and Context**
Resolve https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/8166
Possibly provides good gains for models in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/8362 and https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/7681 (they are encouraged to try with this commit)

title: Make some common macros safer to use.
body:
**Description**
Some macros were defined like this: `#define MACRO(condition, ...) if (condition) do_something`.
This can be problematic if expanded in a context like this:
```
if (condition_1)
  MACRO(condition_2);
else
  // logic for !condition_1
```
The else will associate with MACRO's if and we get unexpected results, e.g., when `condition_1 && !condition_2`.

We can avoid this by wrapping MACRO in `do { ... } while(false)`.

**Motivation and Context**
Clean up code.

title: Add quantization support of GEMM directly with QGemm
body:
**Description**: Describe your changes.
QGemm takes in quantized A, B, C, and quantization parameters of output Y, in which C and quantization parameters of Y are optional. Its output can be quantized or full precision, which depends on whether quantization parameters of Y exists or not. If quant params of Y are provided, the output will be requantized or is full precision. 

Comparing with QLinearMatMul and MatMulInteger, QGemm supports transpose, apha and beta attribute.

The formula for quantized GEMM is:
Y = alpha * scale_a * scale_b * ((A_int8 - zp_a) * (B_int8 - zp_b) + C_int32), in which,
C_int32 is quantized with formula: C_int32 = (beta * C) / (alpha * scale_a * scale_b)
